	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EC delegate explains EU action plan to Caribbean</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 March 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> Writing in the <i>Nation</i> newspaper the EU delegate to Barbados and the eastern Caribbean expressed the view that restructuring support should take the form of budget support deployed through national adaptation strategies implemented over an eight-year period. The delegate stressed the importance of 'moving from tactical attempts to postpone the reform to working together on national strategies making the most of the significant adaptation support that the EU will be making available to ACP sugar producers'. The delegate commended Barbados and St Kitts &amp; Nevis for being 'quite advanced in preparing agricultural diversification strategies, including ideas such as cane fuel and/'branded' sugar.</p><p> His comments came as the final sugar harvest was launched on St Kitts &amp; Nevis. With annual losses to the islands' sugar industry continuing to rise, the impending reform of the EU sugar regime, with its dramatic price reductions would have generated losses which would have 'threatened the capacity of our financial system and our country as a whole', according to agriculture minister Cedric Liburd. The government of St Kitts &amp; Nevis is designing retraining and employment-creation schemes to help manage the costs of adjustment and has established a dedicated 'Transition Office' in the St Kitts Sugar Manufacturing Corporation (SSMC).</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://news.caribseek.com/Saint_Kitts_and_Nevis/article_11185.shtml" target="_self">Press report ( <i>SKNIS News</i> March 15th 2005)</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://news.caribseek.com/Saint_Kitts_and_Nevis/article_11186.shtml" target="_self">Press report ( <i>SKNIS News</i> March 15th 2005)</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.nationnews.com/StoryView.cfm?Record=58721&amp;Section=Local&amp;Current=2005%2D03%2D14%2000%3A00%3A00" target="_self">Press report (the <i>Nation</i> Barbados March 14th 2005)</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Caribbean sugar-dependent economies will face a significant challenge in expeditiously mobilising funds for restructuring programmes given the normal delays faced in securing EDF financing and mobilising funds from any special facility established under the EU annual budget. These problems could be eased if the EC instructed its delegates in ACP sugar-dependent countries to facilitate the deployment of existing NIP funds in support of the drawing up of country-specific sugar-sector strategies and in support of first-phase restructuring activities, using funds the actual disbursement of which is not scheduled until 2007/2008. This would need to be accompanied by the incorporation into the proposed special sugar facility of provisions allowing for retroactive financing to reimburse other NIP activities from which funds have been diverted to support first-phase sugar-sector restructuring activities. This kind of retroactive financing provision would allow ACP sugar-exporting countries to initiate measures to prepare for the impact of EU sugar price reductions rather than simply having to respond to the consequences.</p>
		</div>
		
